author: @epistemophilicmetalhead9454
text: neural network consists of nodes and weights (like slope) and biases (like y intercept) and it's like finding a non-straight line curve that fits your data you start with unknown w's and b's and estimate their values through back propagation input, hidden and output layers. hidden layers' nodes use activation functions like sigmoid, relu, softplus that are curves themselves and 'add' them together to get a final curve as output to predict data input layer has x. x becomes wx+b. then you do activation function f(wx+b) to get a y value. [relu ge it's max(0,x). sigmoid ge it's exp(x)/( exp(x)+1 ) and for softplus it's ln(1+exp(x))   you do this for all x values in the range and you'll get a range of y values that correspond (actually) to a very small range in the activation function [eg: x goes from from 0-1 but wx+b will correspond to a much smaller range of the activation function. so this means that different ranges of the activation function might give rise to different looking curves] each node in the hidden layers will give you one kind of curve and then the calculation keeps on going for how many ever nodes necessary. let's skip to last hidden layer. the curves have been calculated. you have intermediate y values ready. now add all of them to get a different looking final curve. set of y values corresponding to this final curve are your output binary classification: if that y values is close to 1, predict success. if y value is close to 0, predict failure

I thought this would give the same shape of the neural network as in the video?  # With 2 activation functions that are softplus.  modnn <- keras_model_sequential () %>%   layer_dense(units = 2, activation = "softplus",               input_shape = ncol(x)) %>%   layer_dense(units = 1)  # Compile the model after it was set up in the previous step  modnn %>% compile(loss = "mse",                   optimizer = optimizer_rmsprop (),                   metrics = list("mean_absolute_error"))  Train the model 200 times on the train data. author: @firesongs
text: After watching this video, I wanted to check my understanding. Are these the correct steps in building a neural network?  1.	Input 5 Features via the Input layer (eg. n = 5)  2.	Hidden Layer is in charge of fitting the squiggle.  a.	Using those 5 features, it produces different parts of the squiggle. b.	It does this by pushing the 5 features through an activation function you choose (activation function does a nonlinear transformation)  3.	Output Layer adds up the Hidden Layer‚Äôs squiggles (linear combination) and produces final prediction. a.	(Optional) Can push squiggle thru 1 last activation function (Softmax) to give you human interpretable results (a probability).

author: @DrRiq
text: I think the novel value of this video (for me) is that it helps bridge the gap left with 3Blue1Brown's video where he intuites what the NN may be doing, but then reveals that it actually appears random and chaotic, without the sense of order we initially assumed to make sense of it. This video explains that although the particular weights and biases may appear random at first glance, it is through their summation/cancellation that an order emerges. Also, kudos for introducing a new beginner example -- I genuinely did not realise that there were other applications outside of image recognition lol (I am a beginner to this!). As in, yes it's easy for us to look at the simple data and say 'hurr durr why not just model it with a quadratic equation'; but here is a different way to derive values to fit the data on the graph. Which was new to me, so, thanks!

author: @pperez1224
text: Just 2 questions please : there is a symetry in the data , so why is the squiggle not symetric in the end? And why is the max value far above 1 ( its actually 2 )? here are my calculations for the max :-)      // input side     float wi1 = -34.4f;     float bi1 = 2.14f;     float wi2 = -2.52f;     float bi2 = 1.29f;      // output side     float wo1 = -1.3f;     float bo1 = -0.58f / 2;     float wo2 = 2.28f;     float bo2 = -0.58f / 2;      for (float i : new float[]{0.0f, 0.2f, 0.4f, 0.5f, 0.7f, 0.9f, 1f})       {       float squiggle = (float) (Math.log(1 + Math.exp(wi1 * i + bi1)) * wo1 + bo1 +               Math.log(1 + Math.exp(wi2 * i + bi2)) * wo2 + bo2);       System.out.println(i + " -> " + squiggle);       }  You get :  0.0 -> -0.01100103 0.2 -> 2.0568225 0.4 -> 1.3444334 0.5 -> 1.0348316 0.7 -> 0.52345765 0.9 -> 0.14783566 1.0 -> 0.004632659  :-/
